05803nam a22012735i 9780691222073DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912220737 a10.1515/97806912220732doi  a(DE-B1597)572640  a(OCoLC)1226680087  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a1931 aThiele, Leslie Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFriedrich Nietzsche and the Politics of the Soul :bA Study of Heroic Individualism /cLeslie Paul Thiele. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Moral, Political, and Legal Philosophy ;v500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA NOTE ON SOURCES AND CITATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPart I: Heroic Individualism -- tONE. The Heroic -- tTWO. Individualism -- tPart II: The Politics of the Soul -- tTHREE. The Soul as a Plurality -- tFOUR. The Well-Ordered Soul -- tPart III: Incarnations and Ideals -- tFIVE. The Philosopher -- tSIX. The Artist -- tSEVEN. The Saint -- tEIGHT. The Educator and the Solitary -- tNINE. Apotheosis and Laughter: The Overman -- tPart IV: The Circle of Return -- tTEN. Amor Fati and the Eternal Recurrence -- tELEVEN. Becoming Who You Are -- tCONCLUSION -- tWORKS OF NIETZSCHE CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReading Nietzsche's works as the "political biography of his soul," Leslie Thiele presents an original and accessible essay on the great thinker's attempt to lead a heroic life as a philosopher, artist, saint, educator, and solitary. He takes as his point of departure Nietzsche's conception of the soul as a multiplicity of conflicting drives and personae, and focuses on the task Nietzsche allotted himself "to make a cosmos out of his chaotic inheritance." This struggle to "become what you are" by way of a spiritual politics is demonstrated to be Nietzsche's foremost concern, which fused his philosophy with his life. The book offers a conversation with Nietzsche rather than a consideration of the secondary literature, yet it takes to task many prevalent approaches to his work, and contests especially the way we often restrict our encounter with him to conceptual analysis. All deconstructionist attempts to portray him as solely concerned with the destruction of the subject and the dispersion of the self, rather than its unification, are called into question. Often portrayed as the champion of nihilism, Nietzsche here emerges as a thinker who saw his primary task as the overcoming of nihilism through the heroic struggle of individuation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh  aAchilles.  aAeschylus.  aApollonian.  aAristotle.  aAsclepius.  aBeyond Good and Evil.  aBirth of Tragedy, The.  aBrombert, Victor.  aCalypso.  aCrito.  aCyclops.  aDaedalus.  aDaybreak.  aDionysian man.  aDionysian.  aDionysus.  aEcce Homo.  aEckermann.  aEpicurus.  aEuripides.  aGerman philosophy.  aGlaucon.  aHamlet.  aHector.  aHecuba.  aHeraclitus.  aHomer.  aMedusa.  aOdysseus.  aPascal.  aagonism, agonal.  aapotheosis.  aartist.  aasceticism.  aatheism.  aconsciousness.  adecadence.  ademocracy.  adeterminism.  adualism.  aeducation.  aegoism.  aeternal recurrence.  afame.  afatalism.  aheroic individualism.  aindividual, as multiplicity.  ainstincts.  alaughter.  alaws of nature.  aontology.  aperspectivism.  arationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive